liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ABC journalist Nicole Hegarty has asked, "which words in that statement you're relying on to form that view?" In his response, Mr Mundine references the one-page Uluru Statement and other documents that were prepared as part of its development. Mr Mundine's response: As I said, it's a canvass, that 439 words on the front page where the signatures are. And also the 28 pages behind that. The 28 pages behind that, if people read them, and you go through it. And I'm currently, I've got a full article critique of that, of what's on the cover and what's the 28 pages behind. The 28 pages is about the manifesto of how it's going to be put in place and how it's going to be operated, and in that, they put their ideas of the ten points that need to be raised. And they cover a whole wide range of things that people can't get away from and it does talk about sovereignty and it does talk about treaties and it talks about a whole wide range of other things that are in that document. So you just can't ignore that page, those 28 pages. And that's where it comes at. Because it is a challenge to Australian society. For context the statement is one-page long and claims about a longer version of the Uluru Statement stem from a Freedom of information release by the National Indigenous Australians Agency (NIAA) of drafting notes and meeting outcomes from preparatory work for the Uluru statement. An NIAA spokeswoman told CheckMate that the 26-page document in question contained "the one-page Uluru Statement from the Heart, followed by 25 pages of background information and excerpts of regional dialogues that informed [it]".

children.content: ABC journalist
Nicole Hegarty has asked, "which words in that statement you're relying on to form that view?"
In his response, Mr Mundine references the one-page Uluru Statement and other documents that were prepared as part of its development.
Mr Mundine's response:
As I said, it's a canvass, that 439 words on the front page where the signatures are.
And also the 28 pages behind that. The 28 pages behind that, if people read them, and you go through it.
And I'm currently, I've got a full article critique of that, of what's on the cover and what's the 28 pages behind.
The 28 pages is about the manifesto of how it's going to be put in place and how it's going to be operated, and in that, they put their ideas of the ten points that need to be raised.

And they cover a whole wide range of things that people can't get away from and it does talk about sovereignty and it does talk about treaties and it talks about a whole wide range of other things that are in that document.
So you just can't ignore that page, those 28 pages. And that's where it comes at. Because it is a challenge to Australian society.

For context the statement is one-page long and claims about a longer version of the Uluru Statement stem from a Freedom of information release by the National Indigenous Australians Agency (NIAA) of drafting notes and meeting outcomes from preparatory work for the Uluru statement.

An NIAA spokeswoman told CheckMate that the 26-page document in question contained "the one-page Uluru Statement from the Heart, followed by 25 pages of background information and excerpts of regional dialogues that informed [it]".

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Warren Mundine has begun his speech to the National Press Club. "Next month's Referendum is one of the most important in Australia's history," he says. "Australians will have a choice about what kind of nation we want to be: Do we want Australia to be a liberal democracy where all people are equal, where all Australians can be reconciled and moving ahead with a united purpose? Or do we want to be a country where people are divided by race and permanently in conflict with each other over facts of history that cannot be altered?"

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ANZ has been ordered by the Federal Court to to pay a $15 million penalty for misleading customers about funds available in certain credit card accounts. The Australian lender falsely indicated to customers that they could rely on a 'cash advance' from funds stated to be their 'Available Funds' without incurring fees and interest. The error resulted in customers being charged with thousands of dollars in fees while the average remediation paid was around $45 per affected account, according to the Australian Securities & Investments Commission (ASIC) — the regulator which sued ANZ. "Many ANZ customers relied on the account information displayed by the bank and were charged fees that were inconsistent with that information," said ASIC deputy chair Sarah Court. So far, the country's fourth-largest bank has provided remediation payments of more than $8.3 million to about 186,000 accounts that were charged with fees and interest between May 2016 and November 2018. "The court found ANZ breached the ASIC Act and the National Consumer Credit Protection Act," the regulator said. In a separate statement, the lender acknowledged the breach and agreed to further remediation for the period from November 2018 to September 2021. "ANZ accepts responsibility for what has occurred and apologises to its customers, and has addressed the issues that gave rise to the contraventions," the lender said.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ANZ fined $15m for misleading customers over funds

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Qantas shares are losing value as pressure mounts on the chairman Richard Goyder to step down. The airline has also warned higher fuel costs may push ticket prices up. Analyst firm Jefferies has lowered its earning per share (EPS) forecast for Qantas by 14 per cent, but says "positive" customer improvement initiatives along with ongoing strength in demand suggest damage to the brand is fixable. By 12:15pm AEST, Qantas' share price was down 1.5% t o $5.15. It looks even worse when you step back and look at Qantas shares. They have dropped 5.3% in the past week, and have plunged 17.3% in the past month.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Hi everyone — Rachel Pupazzoni jumping in to say hi. The leader on the ASX today is medical imaging company Pro Medicus after securing a $140 million, 10-year contract with the largest not-for-profit healthcare system in Texas, Baylor Scott & White Health. Its shares jumped 9.3 per cent at the open, but have pared back a little to 9 per cent — to be valued at $77.62 a share, shortly after 11am AEST. Pro Medicus will supply cloud-engineered imaging services, starting in the first quarter of 2024. "Baylor Scott & White Health joins our impressive list of IDN and Tier 1 academic clients and represents our first major client in Texas." Dr Sam Hupert, the chief executive of Pro Medicus, told the market: "The scale and scope of our initiative with Baylor Scott & White Health is noteworthy and will include nearly 500 radiologists who will be exposed to the benefits of Visage 7."
